  <span id="freeText12693328260734152986" style="display:none"><i>
  <b>“You will think me cruel, very selfish, but love is always selfish; the more ardent the more selfish.”</b>
</i><br /><br /><b>Victorian novel no. 2</b><br /><br />What a wonderful story! <br /><br />Since I’d never before in my life read anything related to vampires, I planned to read <i>Dracula</i> by Bram Stoker this year; so, I immediately decided to get a copy of that novel and give it a chance during this Victober. However, a friend of mine told me a great piece of advice a few weeks ago: “if you have not read either <i>Dracula</i> or <i>Carmilla</i>, you should try the second one first”. And that’s it, I did it. <br /><br /><b>Carmilla</b> is considered one of the first Vampire novels/novellas, being published in 1872. In this story, Laura, who is the narrator, tells us how she and her father met Carmilla, a young and gorgeous girl who is leaved by her mother at Laura’s house, a remote castle in the middle of a dense forest. After Carmilla appears, certain eerie and unusual situations start to take place in Laura’s life.<br /><br />Trust me, when I finished reading this book I was blown away by the Le Fanu’s ability to create a well written story like this, with a fascinating and mysterious female character such as Carmilla. Besides, the whole story, even when it’s quite short, is so compelling and intriguing that it’s impossible not to want to know more information about its characters and who they are in a deeper way. Despite these facts, the novella is totally worth reading. <br /><br />My favorite part was doubtlessly the ultimate explanation at the end of the book, when finally some of your possible questions throughout the story could be answered. In my opinion, that was such an accurate conclusion that I couldn’t help but be amazed when I read those final paragraphs. <br /><br />In short, this was my first contact with a gothic vampire book, perhaps that’s the reason why I loved it so much, or maybe not. Either way, I’d like to recommend you this book, and I hope you enjoy it as much as I did.</span>
